                        <handDesc><summary>Four different hands (scribe A, B, C, and D) can be distinguished. There are multiple colophons ranging from Ramaḍān 992 to Muḥarram 993 AH, which correspond to the period between September 1584 and January 1585 CE. The anonymous introduction and the Pentateuch (fols 1r-86r) constitute the first. Blank folios, change of quire and hands (scribe C to B), and the smaller number of bifolia in the last quire, clearly suggest a caesura. The second encompasses the Historical Books (fols 86v-195v). In distinction to the first, it is homogenetic and was copied entirely by scribe B. A change of hands (scribe B to A = Faḍlallāh) and quires sets the boundaries with the ensuing block. The third block, thus, ranges from the book of Ezra (fol 196r) to the end of the Prophets (390v). It falls into three sub-sections: Ezra to Job (196r- 232r), Psalms (232v-267v), and the Prophets (268r-390v). These are only indicated by blank folios, yet the change of hands and quires does not coincide with their boundaries. The block was written by scribe A and C, and transits into the following with blank folios, a change of hands and quires. The last quire has a smaller number of folios, which in addition marks a caesura. The last block, copied exclusively by Faḍlallāh, comprises the Sapiental Books, 2 and 5 Maccabees.  A number of blank folios (fols 424v-429r) divide it into two sub-sections. </summary><handNote medium="" xml:id="hand-111">
      <locus from="" to=""/>
      <persName ref="" role=""/>
      <placeName ref=""/>
      <metamark function=""/>
      <origDate when=""/>
      <note>Scribe A discloses his identity on fol 404r (see image 2). His name is Faḍlallāh b. Tādrus b. Yūsuf b. Faḍlallāh b. Naṣrallāh, the priest. He is thus identical to the scribe who entirely copied the Vatican volume and about whom we have already gathered some information. Following many expressions of humbleness, similar to what we have encountered before, he names Qasr al-Shamʿ, i.e. Coptic quarter of Old Cairo, as place of his ministry. He also reveals that the place of production of the Parisian manuscript is the same as in regard to its Vatican sister copy (see above). On fol 404r, following the book of Proverbs, Faḍlallāh states that kāna naskh dhālika bi-l-qāhira al-maḥrūsa bi-khaṭṭ qanṭarat al-mūskī sakn al-ḥaqīr “the place of copying was Cairo, the well-guarded, at Khaṭṭ Qantarat al-Mūskī, the residence of this humble [scribe].” </note>
   </handNote>
                            
                            <handNote medium="" xml:id="hand-112">
                                <locus from="" to=""/>
                                <persName ref="" role=""/>
                                <placeName ref=""/>
                                <metamark function=""/>
                                <origDate/>
                                <note>On fol 387r, in a colophon to the Minor Prophets, scribe C identifies himself as ʿAbd Rabbih b. Muḥammad b. Ahmad b. ʿAbd ar-Raḥmān al-Shaʿrānī al-Anṣārī. His name indicates beyond doubt that he was a Muslim.  His religious affiliation is also confirmed by the use of hijri dates and the Islamic names for months (see below). This detail is not insignificant as it illustrates the confession-transgressing character of the workshop.  </note>
                            </handNote>
